  <!-- Section: Application Process -->
  <section id="application" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Application Process</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Italy's Investor Visa uses a two-stage process: first obtain a "nulla osta" (clearance certificate) from the Invest in Italy Committee, then apply for the visa at your local Italian consulate. The process is faster than many Golden Visas.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={timelineColumns} rows={timelineRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step-by-Step Guide</h3>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Identify Your Investment</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Decide on investment route (startup, SME, company, bonds, or philanthropic). For startup/SME routes, identify the target company from Italy's official registries. For bonds, identify the BTP securities you'll purchase. Consider working with an investment advisor familiar with Italian markets.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Prepare Documentation</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Gather required documents: valid passport, proof of investment funds, investment plan/target identification, health insurance certificate, criminal record check (apostilled), proof of accommodation in Italy (even temporary), and source of funds documentation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Submit Online Pre-Approval Application</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Apply online through the Invest in Italy portal (investorvisa.mise.gov.it) for the nulla osta. Provide investment details, personal information, and supporting documents. The system is English-friendly. No fee for this stage.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Invest in Italy Committee Evaluation</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">The Committee (representatives from multiple ministries) reviews your application. They verify the investment qualifies and check background. By law, they must respond within 30 days. Most applications are approved if documentation is complete.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">5</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Receive Nulla Osta</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">If approved, you receive the nulla osta (clearance certificate) via email. This is valid for 6 months—you must apply for your visa within this period. The nulla osta is essentially pre-approval; consulate processing is usually straightforward after this.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">6</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Apply for Investor Visa at Consulate</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Submit visa application at the Italian consulate in your home country. Bring: nulla osta, passport, photos, health insurance, proof of accommodation, and visa fee (€116). Family members apply simultaneously with supporting documents.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">7</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Receive Visa and Enter Italy</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Visa processing typically takes 15-30 days. Once approved, you receive a 2-year investor visa. Enter Italy and complete your investment within 3 months of arrival.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">8</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Apply for Residence Permit</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Within 8 days of arrival, apply for your Permesso di Soggiorno (residence permit) at your local Questura (police station). Bring proof of investment completion, visa, passport, and accommodation details. The permit is typically issued within 2-4 weeks.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">9</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Complete Investment and Register</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Finalize your investment (transfer funds to startup, purchase bonds, etc.). Obtain documentation proving investment completion. Register for Codice Fiscale (tax code) if not done already. You're now a legal Italian resident.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Processing times:</strong> Italy's Investor Visa is relatively fast. The nulla osta (30 days max) plus consulate processing (15-30 days) means you can have your visa in 2-3 months. Residence permit adds another 2-4 weeks. Total timeline: approximately 3-4 months from application to living in Italy.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

