  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Startup Risk</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The €250,000 startup route is appealing but high-risk. Italian startups, like all startups, can fail. You could lose your entire investment. Only choose this route if you're comfortable with potential total loss and genuinely interested in the business, not just the visa.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting Property Route</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Italy's Investor Visa doesn't include property investment—unlike Greece or Spain. If you want to buy Italian property for residence, you'll need the separate Elective Residence Visa (which requires proving income, not investment). Don't assume you can buy a villa and get investor status.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring Tax Implications</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If you spend 183+ days in Italy, you become Italian tax resident on worldwide income. This can be significant if you have foreign income. Consult an Italian tax advisor before relocating—the new resident regime (€100,000 flat tax on foreign income) may help, but eligibility has conditions.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Waiting to Complete Investment</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must complete your investment within 3 months of entering Italy. Some applicants delay, expecting flexibility. Don't—failure to invest on time can invalidate your visa. Have funds ready and investment structured before arrival.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Choosing Startup Without Due Diligence</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Not all Italian startups are equal. Some visa advisors push specific startups for commissions. Do your own due diligence: review financials, meet founders, understand the business. This is a real investment, not just a visa fee—treat it accordingly.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

