  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work in Italy with the Investor Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Unlike some Golden Visa programs, Italy's Investor Visa includes full work rights. You can work as an employee, start a business, or engage in any professional activity. This makes it attractive for entrepreneurs who want to actively participate in the Italian economy.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get Italian citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Standard naturalization requires 10 years of legal residence. If you're an EU citizen, it's reduced to 4 years. You'll need to pass an Italian language test (B1 level), demonstrate integration, and have clean criminal record. Italy allows dual citizenship, so you typically don't need to renounce your original nationality.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if my startup investment fails?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If your startup fails, you don't automatically lose your residence—but you'll need to make a new qualifying investment to renew. Italy understands startup risk; the key is maintaining compliant status. Many advisors recommend having backup investment capacity if choosing the startup route.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is there a minimum stay requirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          There's no explicit minimum stay for the Investor Visa itself. However, for permanent residence (after 5 years), you generally need to have been primarily resident in Italy. For citizenship (10 years), you must have maintained continuous residence. If you plan to rarely visit Italy, consider Greece's Golden Visa instead.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I buy property with the Investor Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          You can buy property in Italy, but property purchase doesn't qualify for the Investor Visa. You need separate qualifying investment (startup, company, bonds, or donation). However, once you have the visa, you're free to purchase property for living or investment purposes separately.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does the €100,000 flat tax work?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The "new resident" regime allows qualifying individuals to pay a flat €100,000/year on all foreign-sourced income, regardless of amount. This is attractive for high earners with significant foreign income. Requirements include not being Italian tax resident for 9 of the previous 10 years. Consult an Italian tax advisor for eligibility.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
